    bio: "Abu Abdullah Muhammad ibn Battuta was born in Tangier, Morocco, in 1304, into a family of Islamic legal scholars. At the age of twenty-one, he set out on the hajj to Mecca — a journey that was supposed to take perhaps a year but instead stretched into nearly three decades of almost continuous travel across the known world. By the time he finally returned home for good, he had traversed an estimated 73,000 miles, a distance that would not be surpassed by any individual traveler for centuries, covering territories from West Africa to China, from the Volga steppes to the Maldive Islands.\n\nIbn Battuta's travels were shaped by the vast network of the medieval Islamic world, which provided him with a common language of faith, law, and hospitality that opened doors from the courts of Delhi to the trading posts of East Africa. He served as a qadi — an Islamic judge — in the Maldives, narrowly survived shipwrecks in the Indian Ocean, witnessed the Black Death ravaging the Middle East, and dined with sultans, emperors, and khans. His experiences paint an unparalleled portrait of the fourteenth-century world in all its diversity, danger, and interconnection, offering historians details found in no other source about societies from Mali to Sumatra.\n\nUpon his return to Morocco around 1354, the Sultan of Fez commissioned a young scholar named Ibn Juzayy to record Ibn Battuta's accounts in a work known as the Rihla, meaning \"The Journey.\" While some scholars have questioned specific details or suggested literary embellishments, the overwhelming majority of the Rihla's observations have been corroborated by independent evidence, cementing its status as one of the greatest travel narratives ever written. Ibn Battuta died in Morocco around 1368, relatively obscure in his own time compared to his near-contemporary Marco Polo, but now recognized as the most widely traveled individual of the pre-modern era."
